('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:9f24bc5e', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "ll — one letter, one sound: the ‘y’ in ‘yes’", "reading": "<p>The double letter <strong>ll</strong> is never two separate ‘l’ sounds — in most of the Spanish-speaking world it is pronounced like the English <strong>‘y’</strong> in ‘yes’.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"llamar\">llamar</span> — to call</td><td>sounds like ‘ya-MAR’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"calle\">calle</span> — street</td><td>sounds like ‘CA-ye’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"amarillo\">amarillo</span> — yellow</td><td>sounds like ‘a-ma-RI-yo’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"silla\">silla</span> — chair</td><td>sounds like ‘SI-ya’</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>English speakers often say a hard ‘l’ sound (as in the word ‘llama’ mispronounced in English) — resist that instinct.</p>", "question": "How is the ‘ll’ in ‘calle’ pronounced?", "options": ["like the ‘y’ in ‘yes’", "as two separate English ‘l’ sounds run together", "silent — it isn''t pronounced at all", "like the throaty ‘ch’ in ‘loch’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ll = ‘y’ sound: calle sounds like ‘CA-ye’, not ‘CAL-le’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:65ea3abd', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "ch — always the familiar English ‘ch’", "reading": "<p><strong>ch</strong> is one of the easier tricky letters: it always sounds like the English ‘ch’ in ‘chip’ — and it never softens the way it can in French.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"leche\">leche</span> — milk</td><td>‘LE-che’, as in ‘chip’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"ocho\">ocho</span> — eight</td><td>‘O-cho’, as in ‘chip’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"noche\">noche</span> — night</td><td>‘NO-che’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"mucho\">mucho</span> — a lot</td><td>‘MU-cho’</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Because it is so close to the English sound, the real risk is skipping it or swapping it for a soft ‘sh’ — keep it crisp.</p>", "question": "How should you pronounce the ‘ch’ in ‘leche’?", "options": ["like the English ‘ch’ in ‘chip’", "silent — it isn''t pronounced at all", "like a soft French ‘sh’ sound", "like a hard English ‘k’ sound"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ch is always the familiar English ‘ch’ sound — leche = ‘LE-che’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:38afef20', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "ñ — a ‘ny’ glide, not a plain n", "reading": "<p><strong>ñ</strong> (‘eñe’) is a separate letter from ‘n’ and always adds a ‘y’ glide, like the ‘ny’ in ‘canyon’.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"mañana\">mañana</span> — tomorrow</td><td>‘ma-NYA-na’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"cumpleaños\">cumpleaños</span> — birthday</td><td>‘cum-ple-A-nyos’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"pequeño\">pequeño</span> — small</td><td>‘pe-QUE-nyo’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"año\">año</span> — year</td><td>‘A-nyo’</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Dropping the tilde and saying a plain ‘n’ is a very common English-speaker error — the glide is essential, not optional decoration.</p>", "question": "What does the tilde on ‘ñ’ change about the sound?", "options": ["it adds a ‘y’ glide, giving ‘ny’", "it makes the letter completely silent, with no sound", "it turns the n into an ‘m’ sound", "nothing — ñ and n sound identical"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ñ = ‘ny’, as in cumpleaños (‘cum-ple-A-nyos’) — never a plain n."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:a42ca869', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "j and h — similar on the page, opposite in sound", "reading": "<p>These two letters trip learners up because they sit close together conceptually, yet do opposite things.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><strong>j</strong> → throaty /x/</td><td><span data-say=\"ojo\">ojo</span>, <span data-say=\"naranja\">naranja</span>, <span data-say=\"trabajar\">trabajar</span></td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>h</strong> → always silent</td><td><span data-say=\"hospital\">hospital</span>, <span data-say=\"hoy\">hoy</span>, <span data-say=\"ahora\">ahora</span></td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>j</strong> is pronounced from the back of the throat, like the Scottish ‘loch’ — never like an English ‘j’ (as in ‘jam’). <strong>h</strong> is never pronounced at all, even at the start of a word.</p>", "question": "Which statement correctly contrasts j and h?", "options": ["j is a throaty sound; h is always silent", "j is silent; h is a throaty sound instead", "both letters are completely silent in Spanish", "both letters sound like an English ‘j’ in ‘jam’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "j = throaty /x/ (ojo); h = never pronounced (hospital = ‘os-pi-TAL’)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:f5a9383d', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "r vs rr — a quick tap or a strong roll?", "reading": "<p>Spanish has two different r-sounds, and mixing them up can change the meaning of a word entirely.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td>single <strong>r</strong> between vowels → one quick tap</td><td><span data-say=\"pero\">pero</span> (but), <span data-say=\"hablar\">hablar</span> (to speak)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>rr</strong>, or <strong>r</strong> at the start of a word → strongly rolled</td><td><span data-say=\"cerrar\">cerrar</span> (to close), <span data-say=\"sonreír\">sonreír</span> (to smile), <span data-say=\"perro\">perro</span> (dog)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The signature exam trap is the minimal pair <span data-say=\"pero\">pero</span> (‘but’) vs <span data-say=\"perro\">perro</span> (‘dog’) — say the wrong one and the sentence stops making sense. <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> Higher-tier read-aloud texts pack several of these r-sounds into one sentence, so practise the switch.</p>", "question": "What is the difference between ‘pero’ and ‘perro’?", "options": ["a single tap vs a strongly rolled r, and the meaning changes completely", "nothing at all — the two words are pronounced in exactly the same identical way", "‘pero’ has a silent r and ‘perro’ does not", "only the stress moves to a different syllable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "pero (single tap, ‘but’) vs perro (rolled rr, ‘dog’) — a classic minimal pair."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:learn:894b33e6', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "v and b — the same soft ‘b’ sound", "reading": "<p>In Spanish, <strong>v</strong> and <strong>b</strong> are pronounced almost identically — a soft ‘b’, made without fully closing the lips. Spanish speakers do not distinguish them the way English does.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"verde\">verde</span> — green</td><td>soft ‘b’, not an English ‘v’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"verdad\">verdad</span> — truth</td><td>soft ‘b’, not an English ‘v’</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"vivir\">vivir</span> — to live</td><td>soft ‘b’ at the start too</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"beber\">beber</span> — to drink</td><td>compare: also a soft ‘b’</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The letter''s own name — <span data-say=\"uve\">uve</span> — is a useful reminder: it borrows the ‘b’ sound, not an English ‘v’.</p>", "question": "How does Spanish ‘v’ (as in ‘verde’) sound?", "options": ["almost exactly like a soft ‘b’ sound", "exactly like an English ‘v’, as in ‘van’", "like an English ‘f’ sound instead", "it is completely silent"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Spanish v and b share the same soft ‘b’-like sound — verde is not an English ‘v’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v:misc:102ccc54', 'spanish', 'spanish:p-2-tricky-letters-ll-ch-j-h-r-v', 'P.2 Tricky Letters: ll, ch, ñ, j, h, r, v', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Pronouncing ‘ll’ (as in llamar) as two separate English ‘l’ sounds.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ‘ll’ is a single ‘y’ sound: llamar sounds like ‘ya-MAR’.</p>", "question": "How should ‘ll’ in ‘llamar’ sound?", "options": ["like the English ‘y’ in ‘yes’", "like two separate English ‘l’ sounds run together", "like the throaty j sound instead", "silent, with no sound at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ll is a single ‘y’ sound, never two ‘l’ sounds."}'::jsonb),
